{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512416"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:54:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:54:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11888"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11888"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.06,0.19,0.54,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4488"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107208"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4488"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11888"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89662"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1637"},{"type":"tags","id":"4173"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6586"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6592"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18185"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18432"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39734"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43277"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48002"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107208"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with heavy menstrual bleeding and pain. Her periods have been regular since the age of 13 and she has no intermenstrual bleeding. Her periods have become increasingly heavy over the last 3 years. In the first two days of her period, she changes pads 8-9 times in a day and has 7/10 lower abdominal cramping pain, for which she takes naproxen regularly. She often bleeds through to her bedsheets overnight and floods during the day. She also experiences a deep pain on intercourse and she is currently using barrier contraception. She does not experience any pain on urination or defaecation. She is keen to avoid surgery if possible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Bimanual examination appears normal. A trans-vaginal pelvic ultrasound is performed and is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance and further review if symptoms worsen","Pelvic CT","Coagulation studies","Combined oral contraceptive","Laparoscopy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with menorrhagia, dyspareunia and dysmenorrhoea, all of which are highly suspicious of mild-moderate endometriosis, particularly in this age group. Bimanual examination and ultrasound examination are often normal in this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFirst-line treatment for mild-moderate endometriosis is regular NSAIDs and hormonal suppression. Thus, a trial of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecombined oral contraceptive\u003C/strong\u003E would be the most appropriate initial step in this patient\u0027s management. This aligns with the patient\u0027s preference to avoid surgery if possible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, it is important to note that the combined oral contraceptive pill must be taken daily. It is often forgotten by patients, making it significantly less effective. Thus, many patients may opt for a long-acting reversible form of contraception (LARC) such as the levonorgestrel intrauterine device (which offers the additional benefit of being 99.95% effective in preventing pregnancy and can be effective for up to five years with minimal side effects).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA pelvic CT\u003C/strong\u003E is only indicated for endometriosis where there is concern for bowel or bladder involvement. As she has no dysuria or pain on defaecation, a CT scan is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic evaluation\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard diagnostic test for endometriosis, but it is an invasive investigation. Given she has no bowel or bladder involvement, has not tried any treatment, and is keen to avoid surgery, it is recommended that she trial pharmacological therapy first. If she had persistent symptoms despite the trial, proceeding to laparoscopy would be indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoagulation studies\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as at the age of 27, it is extremely unlikely that this is the first presentation of an undiagnosed clotting disorder, especially considering menarche started at 13 and her periods have only become heavy over the last 3 years. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and further review\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the severity of her symptoms and their impact on her quality of life. Active management is required rather than a watch-and-wait approach.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mild to moderate endometriosis is treated with regular NSAIDs and hormonal suppression.","Laparoscopy is often diagnostic for endometriosis in those with normal ultrasound"],"references":["Endometriosis clinical practice guidelines. In: RANZCOG. [online]. 2021. Available at: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Endometriosis-Clinical-Practice-Guideline.pdf","How effective is my contraceptive method. In: SHINESA [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.shinesa.org.au/media/2016/04/Efficacy-of-contraception-methods.pdf","Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Endometriosis: Clinical Practice Guideline. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2021 [cited 2025 Jun 26]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Endometriosis-Clinical-Practice-Guideline.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89662"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11888"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89662"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-26T09:18:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-26T10:02:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4488"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107208"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"head